Very upsetting to hear about young Chetana Raj's demise, who opted for a liposuction surgery and ended up losing her life. This is a sad conversation, but one that must be had. 
Yes, we all want to look our best, and we all have certain insecurities that we want to take care of.. However, the first and most important thing that needs to be considered and taken into account is SAFETY.
In my conversation with Chaiti Narula and Dr. Kiran Sethi for India Today, I talk about firstly, the taboo around cosmetic procedures. Why is this a big problem? It prevents individuals from asking questions openly and seeking the right and complete information - which is the first step towards ensuring undergoing a safe procedure. 

Secondly, I talk about what needs to be kept in mind, from a patient's perspective, before making a decision. 

And finally, most importantly, I talk about how important the role of the doctor is. While every procedure, small and big, has a certain risk attached, and when these risks occur - no one person is to blame. However, the doctor, has certain responsibilities that come with his/her knowledge and expertise. One, letting the patient know about the risks. Two, making sure they conduct the procedure in an appropriate setting. Three, to correctly assess the patient and see if he or she is an appropriate candidate for said procedure. Four, to say NO to the patient when necessary. And this is the most important. Sometimes, a good doctor is the one that says no when needed. 

In every case, there are various contributing factors. The doctor, the patient, the people around the patient, social media.. and so on. However, few things that are in our hands need to be taken care of. What do you think?

PRP (platelet-rich plasma) therapy for hair loss is a three-step medical treatment in which a person’s blood is drawn, processed, and then injected into the scalp.

•Strengthens the hair from thinning of the existing hair. 
•Increases the diameter of the existing hair.

•Non-allergenic process.

*PROGENITOR*
•ProGenitor is an innovative and revolutionary treatment in which the area on the scalp which requires hair growth is injected with clinically processed tissue taken from the scalp itself and using the regenerative activity of the progenitor cells in it for hair regrowth.

latestIgtvVideos.title: *Acne Scars (Part- 2)*
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Two kinds of Acne scars 
•Coloured Scars-red , brown , grey scar & black mark.

•Textural Scars-like  pitted scars, boxcar scars, rolling scars& Ice-prick scars

*COLOUR SCARS*
•RED SCAR - simply the initial stage of inflammation or then they are Hypertrophic scars , when there is lot of tension around a healing wound. These scars are thick
 and raised, and often red in colour.

• BROWN SCAR- Scar exposed to sunlight during the healing process can cause the scar tissue to get pigmented.

• GREY SCAR- A gray pale or bluish tint to the skin are due to tissue response to injury - we call it PIH .

•BLACK MARK- Black mark on the face result from hyperPigmentation, which is a common skin condition that occurs when the skin produces too much melanin.

*TEXTURAL SCARS*
•PITTED SCARS- Deep pitted acne scars, also known as atrophic scars. They generally appear due to the loss of tissue during cell regeneration that eventually leaves behind a skin that has a pitted experience.

• BOXCAR SCARS- A boxcar scar is a round or oval depression in your skin that’s left behind after certain forms of acne heal. Some boxcar scars can look red or dark brown, but others are the same color as the skin around them.

•ROLLING SCARS- Rolling scars are a common type of scarring that can occur as a result of the acne healing process. They appear as indents in the skin and tend to measure a few millimetres wide.

•ICE PRICK SCARS- Ice pick scars are a type of acne scar. Due to their depth and narrow impressions, ice pick scars are more severe than boxcar, atrophic, or other types of acne scars.

Summer + Acne = The Struggle is Real ☀️🔥”

Breakouts love summer. Why?
Because your skin is battling:

🔸 Excess sweat + oil
🔸 Humidity clogging your pores
🔸 Sunscreens not meant for acne-prone skin
🔸 Dust + pollution sticking to sweaty skin
🔸 Over-washing or skipping moisturizer

Here’s how to keep your skin summer-safe:
✅ Switch to a gel-based or non-comedogenic sunscreen
✅ Use a gentle foaming cleanser twice a day
✅ Don’t skip moisturizer — go for lightweight, oil-free ones
✅ Shower right after sweating
✅ Blot, don’t wipe — avoid friction!

Summer glow ≠ summer breakouts!
Smart swaps = happy skin 🌞🧴

Tag someone who always breaks out in summer & save this for your skincare checklist!

#SummerAcne #HeatBreakouts #DermatologistTips

Those pesky body breakouts (aka backne, buttne & shoulder acne) aren’t just a summer thing — and no, it’s not always about hygiene!

Here’s what could be triggering it:
🔸 Sweat + friction from tight clothes
🔸 Clogged pores from oils & product buildup
🔸 Skipping showers after workouts
🔸 Dandruff – yes, scalp flakes clog pores down your back!
🔸 Excessive protein intake (especially whey) can spike oil production & worsen acne
🔸 Hormonal changes

🧴 Scalp check is a must — a clean scalp = clearer back!

Tips to prevent & treat it:
✅ Use salicylic acid or benzoyl peroxide body wash
✅ Exfoliate 1–2x/week (gently)
✅ Wear breathable, loose-fitting clothes
✅ Shower right after sweating
✅ Switch to non-comedogenic body care
✅ Evaluate your protein intake — balance is key!

Your skin talks — listen from head to toe.
Share this with someone who needs to hear it!
